Human Dignity: "Dignity of man" or "human dignity" mentioned in the constitution
Right to Overthrow Government: Citizens explicitly granted right to depose the government under certain circumstances
Amparo: Right to judicial remedy for government violations of certain individual rights
Indigenous Voting: Voting rights for indigenous peoples specifically protected
Indigenous Representation: Indigenous people granted special representation in the central government
Form Indigenous Political Parties: Right of indigenous peoples to form political parties specifically protected
Indigenous Tax Exemption: Indigenous people exempted from taxation for certain activities
Indigenous Exemption for Illegal Activit: Indigenous people allowed to participate in certain activities illegal for non-indigenous groups
Indigenous Internal Governance: Indigenous people granted special rights to internal governance
Form Parties: Right to form political parties generally protected
Universal Adult Suffrage: Voting rights for all adults protected
State Duty to Protect Culture: State required to protect or promote culture or cultural rights
Jury Trial: Juries or other citizen participation required for decision-making in criminal trials
Victims' Rights: Rights of crime victims specifically protected
Extradition of Criminals: Extradition of suspected or convicted criminals prohibited
Collection of Evidence: Search, seizure, or other evidentiary collection regulated
Pre-Trial Release: Right to pre-trial release specifically protected
Habeas Corpus: Right to protection from unjustified restraint specifically protected
No Punishment Without Law: Punishments must be in accordance with legal rules
Appeal: Right to appeal judicial decisions specifically protected
Corporal Punishment Banned: Whipping and other physical punishments prohibited
Due Process: Right to due process of law specifically protected
Examine Witnesses: Right to examine or confront witnesses in legal proceedings protected
Ex Post Laws Banned: Laws retroactively altering legal status of various activities prohibited
Redress for False Imprisonment: Right of compensation or remedy for false imprisonment or judicial error protected
Fair Trial: Right to a fair trial specifically protected
Speedy Trial: Right to a speedy trial specifically protected
Presumption of Innocence: Innocence presumed in trials at law
Trial in Native Language: Right to interpreter or trial in a language in the accused person's language protected
Juvenile Criminal Rights: Juveniles given special rights or status in criminal procedure
Double Jeopardy Banned: Multiple trials for the same crime prohibited
Protection Against Self-Incrimination: Right to silence or protection from self-incrimination for accused persons
Counsel: Right to counsel for indicted or arrested persons
Birthright Citizenship: All citizens born in a country's national territory automatically granted citizenship
Renounce Citizenship: Citizens given right to renounce citizenship
Equality Before Law: Non-discrimination or equality before law specifically protected
Gender Equality: Discrimination on basis of gender prohibited
Nationality Equality: Discrimination on basis of nationality prohibited
Country of Origin Equality: Discrimination on basis of country of origin prohibited
Racial Equality: Discrimination on basis of race prohibited
Language Equality: Discrimination on basis of language prohibited
Religious Equality: Discrimination on basis of religion prohibited
Sexual Orientation Equality: Discrimination on basis of sexual orientation prohibited
Age Equality: Discrimination on basis of age prohibited
Disability Equality: Discrimination on basis of mental or physical disability prohibited
Color Equality: Discrimination on basis of color prohibited
Creed Equality: Discrimination on basis of creed or beliefs prohibited
Social Status Equality: Discrimination on basis of social status prohibited
Financial Equality: Discrimination on basis of property ownership prohibited
Tribe/Clan Equality: Discrimination on basis of tribe or clan prohibited
Party Equality: Discrimination on basis of political party membership prohibited
Parentage Equality: Discrimination on basis of parentage prohibited
Access to Information: Right to view government files or documents
Protection of Reputation: Right to protect one's reputation from libelous actions
Separation of Church and State: Explicit separation of church and state
Expropriation of Property: State may take private property for public use
Fair Compensation: Right to just, fair, or equal payment for work
Unions: Right to form or join trade unions
Minimum Standard of Living: Right to an adequate or reasonable standard of living
Testate: Right to transfer property freely after death
Intellectual Property: General reference to intellectual property rights
Form Business: Right to conduct or establish a business
Consumer Rights: Consumer rights or consumer protection specifically mentioned
Support for Elderly: Right to financial support for elderly persons
Support for Unemployed: Right to financial support for unemployed persons
Support for Disabled: Right to financial support for disabled persons
Support for Children: Right to financial support for children or orphans
Property: Right to own property specifically mentioned
Free Market: Right to a free or competitive market specifically mentioned
Benefits of Science: Right to enjoy the benefits of scientific progress
Safe Working Environment: Right to a safe working environment
Matrimonial Equality: Equality between partners in a marriage
Self-Determination: Constitution explicitly grants right to select fundamental political and social principles without external compulsion
Slavery Banned: Constitutional prohibition on slavery, servitude, or forced labor
Cruel Treatment Prohibited: Cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment banned
Movement: Freedom of movement from place to place
Opinion: Freedom of opinion, thought, or conscience
Development of Person: Individual right to self-determination or free development of personality
Conscientious Objectors: Right to exemption from military service for conscientious objectors
Asylum: Protections for stateless individuals or refugees, or a general right to asylum
Environment: Protection or preservation of environment mentioned
Access to Higher Education: Equal access to higher education guaranteed
